{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488812"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:58:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:58:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"549"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/549"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.15,0.01,0.02,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"549"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42480"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/549"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"549"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27458"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"456"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5060"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5306"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42480"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a three-week history of right upper quadrant pain and lethargy. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and drinks 60 gm alcohol a day. He works as a sheep farmer. On physical examination he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable apart from some tenderness in the right upper quadrant. A CT scan of the abdomen is performed and a representative slice is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hydatid cyst of the liver","Liver abscess","Acute cholecystitis","Metastatic liver disease","Hepatocellular carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHydatid disease used to be common disease in sheep-rearing areas in Australia, where man became an inadvertent secondary host, after becoming infected from the primary hosts - dogs. Deworming of pets and working dogs has lowered the incidence of the disease in Australia, although hydatid remains relatively common in some parts of the world, such as Turkey. In endemic regions the prevalence of hydatid varies between 1% - 10% of the population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost cases of hydatid cyst are incidental findings and have a characteristic calcified rim. In addition, the contents of a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydatid cyst \u003C/strong\u003Etend to be homogenous - apart from the daughter cysts and \u0027hydatid sand.\u0027 This patient has a typical hydatid cyst with visible daughter cysts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver abscess\u003C/strong\u003E commonly present with infective symptoms including fever and malaise. On imaging, liver abscess present as a solid, single or multilocular cavity with possible gas collection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute cholecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a less likely diagnosis due to the duration of the symptoms. Patients with acute cholecystitis usually present with acute severe right upper quadrant abdominal pain. It is also unlikely to diagnose acute cholecystitis with this film as the slice does not feature the gallbladder/gallbladder fossa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELiver lesions due to \u003Cstrong\u003Emetastatic liver disease\u003C/strong\u003E present as multiple lobulated solid lesions with possible central necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatocellular carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E clinically presents with jaundice, ascites, and constitutional symptoms of anorexia and weight loss. On CT imaging, hepatocellular carcinoma lesions is characteristically more hypervascular and solid than cystic.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Contents of a hydatid cyst on CT scan tend to be homogenous - apart from the daughter cysts and \u0027hydatid sand\u0027"],"references":["Gomez I Gavara C, L\u00f3pez-And\u00fajar R, Belda Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez T, Ramia \u00c1ngel JM, Moya Herraiz \u00c1, et al. Review of the treatment of liver hydatid cysts. World J Gastroenterol. 2015;21(1):124-31. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4284328/","Choi JY, Lee JM, Sirlin CB. CT and MR imaging diagnosis and staging of hepatocellular carcinoma: part I. Development, growth, and spread: key pathologic and imaging aspects. Radiology. 2014;272(3):635-54. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4263631/","Namasivayam S, Martin DR, Saini S. Imaging of liver metastases: MRI. Cancer Imaging. 2007;7(1):2. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1804118/#:~:text=The%20pattern%20of%20tumor%20vascularity,melanoma%20and%20thyroid%20carcinoma%20(Fig.","Alsaif HS, Venkatesh SK, Chan DS, Archuleta S. CT appearance of pyogenic liver abscesses caused by Klebsiella pneumoniae. Radiology. 2011;260(1):129-38. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21460028/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27458"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"549"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14039"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14039"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1e64227b-d964-455e-97b4-be30c9d5a473.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1e64227b-d964-455e-97b4-be30c9d5a473.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":450,"height":376}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27458"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-02-11T12:23:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-02-11T12:23:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"549"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42480"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"